06537nam a22009255i 9781644693926DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816446939267 a10.1515/97816446939262doi  a(DE-B1597)549226  a(OCoLC)1202625546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPJ5129.F57bB56 2020 7aLIT0200002bisacsh04a839.18/309223  aKP 5270qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/81358:00aBlooming Spaces :bThe Collected Poetry, Prose, Critical Writing, and Letters of Debora Vogel /ced. by Anastasiya Lyubas. 1aBoston, MA : bAcademic Studies Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (436 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews of Poland00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tDebora Vogel’s Blooming Spaces: An Introduction -- tPART ONE. The Transformation of Form: Essayistic Art -- tEssays on Literature and Poetics -- tEssays on Art, Artists, and the Applied Arts -- tEssays on Socio-Critical Issues -- tPART TWO. “An Attempt at a New Style”: Poetry -- tSelections from Day Figures (1930) -- tSelections from Mannequins (1934) -- tPART THREE. “Marching Soldiers and Blooming Acacias”: Prose -- tSelections from Acacias Bloom: Montage (1935/36) -- tPART FOUR. From Lviv to New York: Letters (1924–1940) -- tPART FIVE. “Distilling the Figure of Thought”: Reviews and Polemics around Vogel’s Work -- tReviews of Day Figures (1930) and Mannequins (1934) -- tReviews of Acacias Bloom: Discussions of the Yiddish Edition of Akatsyes blien (1935) -- tReviews of the Polish Edition of Akacje kwitną (1936) -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis ground-breaking collection features the oeuvre of Debora Vogel (1900-1942), a Modernist Polish and Yiddish writer, philosopher, translator, and art critic. The author’s poems are examples of Cubist-Constructivist experimentation in a language that is at once lyrical and philosophical.Vogel’s poetry challenges every notion of writing in Yiddish literature from the author’s lifetime to ours. The writer’s prose collection transplants experiments in photography, film, and painting, into the literary medium. Vogel’s articles deal with a variety of topics ranging from abstract art, and individual artists like Marc Chagall and Fernand Leger, to matters of applied arts, including discussions of the interiors of modern apartments, the typography of children’s books, and an overview of fashion exhibitions. In addition, Vogel’s essays examine racism and anti-Semitism, the tasks of progressive intellectuals’ engagement in the society, and the use of literary montage as a way literature ‘does politics.’ Vogel’s extensive travels to Berlin, Stockholm, Vienna, and Paris, and her intimate familiarity with the cityscapes of her native Lwów are reflected in her writings. Vogel’s multimodal writing could be read in conjunction with Giorgio de Chirico’s, Pablo Picasso’s, or El Lissitsky’s paintings, Max Ernst’s painterly and writerly experiments, or Fritz Lang’s, Dziga Vertov’s, and Sergei Eisenstein’s films. Lyubas situates Vogel as the key, yet unrecognized figure for thought and literature of the early and late 20th century, as well as a thinker whose insights are crucial to grasp the contemporary socio-political issues. This is the first collection of Vogel’s writings in English translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAaron Glantz-Leyeles.  aBruno Schulz.  aJewish writers.  aMarcus Ehrenpres.  aMelech Ravitch.  aPolish writes.  aShlomo Bickel.  aYiddish Modernists.  aYiddish writers.1 aLyubas, Anastasiya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBo